---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import OpportunityCard from '@/components/OpportunityCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Optimum Nutrition vs Myprotein — PDP Competitor Analysis">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">Competitor Analysis: Optimum Nutrition vs Myprotein</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Product Detail Page &mdash; Analysed 8 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      Optimum Nutrition is the world's best-selling whey protein brand, built on a reputation for
      clinical-grade quality and consistency rather than value or range. Their Gold Standard 100%
      Whey PDP was compared against Myprotein's Impact Whey Protein PDP. ON's page is lean by
      design — fewer sections, more editorial weight — but two review-intelligence patterns stand
      out as genuine gaps: a review attribute summary surfaced directly below the star rating above
      the fold, and an AI-generated review synthesis with topic-based filtering in the reviews
      section. Both make ON's social proof feel more informative at a glance, despite Myprotein
      having a significantly larger review dataset.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="opportunities-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Opportunities for Myprotein</h2>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Review attribute highlights beside the star rating"
      competitor="Optimum Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,conversion"
      opportunityId="review-attribute-highlights"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Directly below the star rating and review count, ON displays a short inline callout:
        <strong>"Highly rated by customers for: Delivery Speed, Taste and Mixability, Value for Money"</strong>.
        Each attribute is a clickable link that filters the reviews section to show only reviews
        mentioning that dimension. The callout appears above the product bullets and add-to-cart
        area — it is the first thing a user reads after the aggregate score.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/optimum-nutrition-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/on-atf-detail.png" alt="Optimum Nutrition PDP showing 'Highly rated by customers for: Delivery Speed, Taste and Mixability, Value for Money' directly below the star rating" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A star rating tells a user how well-liked a product is. An attribute summary tells them
        <em>why</em>. For a shopper who is undecided between two protein powders with similar ratings,
        seeing "Taste and Mixability" called out explicitly is a significantly stronger signal than
        "4.4 stars". It collapses the work of reading dozens of reviews into a three-word reassurance.
        The clickable links also give curious users a direct path to filtered evidence — reducing
        the friction of finding relevant reviews without requiring search or sorting.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein surfaces a Trustpilot aggregate score and total count on the PDP but does not
        break reviews down by attribute anywhere above the fold. With 210,000+ reviews on Impact
        Whey alone, the data to surface attribute-level highlights is clearly there — the question
        is whether it is structured in a way that supports this. Even a static, editorially curated
        version ("Customers love the taste variety and value per serving") in the area near the
        star rating would provide this signal without requiring a full review platform integration.
        A dynamic version powered by review tagging would be the stronger implementation.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="AI-generated review summary with topic filter chips"
      competitor="Optimum Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,content"
      opportunityId="ai-review-summary"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        At the top of the reviews section, before any individual review is shown, ON displays a
        paragraph-length AI-synthesised summary of what customers say: <em>"Customers praise its
        great taste, easy mixing, and high value, making it a top choice for serious athletes."</em>
        Below this is a "Read summary by topics" CTA. Directly below the search and sort controls
        sits a row of topic filter chips — "size", "ingredients", "results", "absorption", "quality",
        "weight", "smell", "taste" — each filtering the review list to show only reviews that mention
        that topic.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/optimum-nutrition-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/on-reviews-section.png" alt="Optimum Nutrition reviews section showing AI summary paragraph, topic filter chips, and review helpfulness voting" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        No one reads 1,725 reviews. An AI synthesis lets a user get the substance of the community's
        verdict in ten seconds. For high-review-count products, the reviews section risks becoming
        noise rather than signal — the summary resolves this. The topic chips extend the utility:
        a user who cares specifically about mixability can filter to only those reviews rather than
        hunting through pages. Together these patterns turn the reviews section from a scrollable
        wall of text into a structured, navigable knowledge base.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's Impact Whey has 210,000+ reviews — a dataset that makes ON's 1,725 look
        nascent by comparison. Yet the reviews section on Myprotein's PDP is a standard paginated
        list with star and sort filters, but no synthesis, no topic navigation, and no AI summary.
        The opportunity here is significant: a product with this review volume is exactly where
        an AI summary would be most useful and most credible. Even a static editorial summary
        (updated quarterly) would be a meaningful step. Topic chips mapped to common review themes
        — flavour, mixability, value, results — would be relatively low effort to implement against
        an existing tagged review corpus.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Areas Where Myprotein Already Leads</h2>
    <p>
      Myprotein's review volume (210,000+ vs ON's 1,725 for this product) is a substantial trust
      advantage that no pattern on ON's PDP can fully compensate for — breadth of social proof at
      scale is difficult to replicate. Myprotein's flavour range for Impact Whey (50+ flavours)
      far exceeds ON's Gold Standard offering, and this is communicated clearly through the flavour
      selector on the PDP. Myprotein also has a Subscribe &amp; Save option, which ON's PDP does
      not prominently feature. ON's PDP is noticeably sparse below the fold — heavy on editorial
      imagery and light on product information — where Myprotein's structured content tabs (nutrition,
      ingredients, reviews) give users more ways to explore without navigating away.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Competitor Context</h2>
    <p>
      Optimum Nutrition (owned by Glanbia since 2008) is the defining brand in mainstream whey
      protein globally. Gold Standard is consistently the world's best-selling whey, sold in
      over 90 countries. Their positioning is built on quality assurance, clinical formulation,
      and athlete endorsements rather than price or flavour innovation. Their target audience is
      serious gym-goers and athletes who are brand-loyal and research-driven. The PDP reflects
      this: it is confident rather than persuasive, leaning on the product's reputation and
      award credentials rather than detailed ingredient storytelling. The review patterns they
      have built are worth noting precisely because they serve a deliberative, trust-led shopper —
      the same type that Myprotein increasingly needs to convert as it moves beyond its value-led
      positioning.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="screenshots-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Page Screenshots</h2>
    <div class="screenshot-grid">
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">Optimum Nutrition — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/optimum-nutrition-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/on-full-desktop.png" alt="Optimum Nutrition Gold Standard Whey PDP full page desktop screenshot" />
      </div>
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">Myprotein — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/optimum-nutrition-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/myprotein-full-desktop.png" alt="Myprotein Impact Whey Protein PDP full page desktop screenshot" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .opportunities-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .screenshot-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; }
  .screenshot-col img { width: 100%; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08); display: block; margin-top: 8px; }
  .screenshot-label { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.55; margin: 0; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }
  .screenshots-section { margin-top: 48px; }
</style>
